This is a collaborative Tutorial created by Rishabh Baral and Christopher Adewunmi

Part 1: Setting the Scene¶

In this tutorial, we will attempt to show prospective NBA owners which teams have spent well in the past and how, in today's money-driven NBA, to replicate their successes.

The first order of business for any new team is to be accepted entry to the league by the commissioner. Luckily, the ownership group has just recieved the following letter from commissioner Adam Silver:

Dear Seattle Ownership Group,

I am pleased to inform you that the NBA Board of Governors has approved your application to become an NBA team beginning in the 2023-24 season. We are thrilled to welcome you to the league and are excited about the potential for your city to become a great basketball market.

As you prepare for your inaugural season, please know that the NBA is committed to supporting you every step of the way. From marketing and ticket sales to player development and league operations, we will work closely with you to ensure your success both on and off the court.

Please take some time to review the league's rules and regulations, as well as our expectations for ownership and team management. We believe that your ownership group has the vision, expertise, and resources necessary to build a successful NBA franchise, and we look forward to seeing your team compete at the highest level.

Thank you for your commitment to the NBA, and we wish you all the best as you embark on this exciting new journey.

Sincerely,

Adam Silver NBA Commissioner

To celebrate their success, the ownership group has hired you as their manager of operations, the position handling team payroll and signings.

Your Offer Letter is as follows:

Dear Applicant,

We are pleased to offer you the position of Director of Operations for our new NBA team beginning in the 2023-24 season. The NBA Board of Governors has approved our application, and we are excited to welcome you to our organization.

Your experience and expertise make you an excellent fit for this role, and we believe you will be an integral part of our success. As Director of Operations, you will be responsible for overseeing the day-to-day activities of the team, including logistics, scheduling, and team travel.

We are committed to providing you with the support and resources necessary to excel in this role. From access to the best facilities and equipment to a talented and dedicated staff, we will work closely with you to ensure your success.

Please take some time to review the details of this offer, including the terms and conditions of your employment, salary and benefits, and other important information. We are confident that you will find this opportunity to be both challenging and rewarding.

Thank you for your interest in our organization, and we look forward to working with you as we build a successful NBA franchise.

Seattle Owneship Group]

Part 2: Beginning your Duties¶

In order to start, the director of operations from the nearest team to you, Portland, has kindly linked you a CSV file with all the data he had collected.

His email to you reads as follows:

Dear Seattle Director of Operations,

I hope this email finds you well. I wanted to reach out to you regarding the upcoming NBA season and the exciting opportunity for our teams to work together.

As Director of Operations for the Portland TrailBlazers, I am excited to connect with you and your team. I believe that our organizations can learn from each other and collaborate on best practices for success.

To that end, I wanted to let you know that I will be sending you a CSV file in the coming days that contains team data from each season since 1985. This information will provide valuable insights into our team's history and strategies for success.

I look forward to hearing your thoughts and feedback on the data. Please let me know if you have any questions or if there is anything else I can do to support you and your team.

Thank you for your time, and I look forward to working witht you.

Be regards,

[Director of Operadtions, Portla TrailBlazers]

It's now been about two days since the email and he has sent you the CSV file.

And now that we have cleaned our data, we can use it for analysis.

Part 4: Performing Exploratory Data Analysis (Splitting, Collating, and Graphing)¶

Now, in order to perform an analysis that processes the data through time, we need to split the data into groups.

We will do this with pandas' cut function. This function will help us by creating however many groups we specify (5 in this case).

In [25]:
NBA_Data['bins'] = pd.cut(x = NBA_Data['Season'], bins = 5)

If we type in the name of our dataframe, we can see that there is a new column indicating the group that each data point belongs to.

In [27]:

Now that we know how many of our 1037 data points fall into each category, we can begin splitting the table into minitables, one for each period. This will make analysis infinitely easier and will allow us to see a comparison between teams in each period, separately.

To split the table, we will query the larger dataframe using the iloc command in order to retrieve just those rows from the table. In each row, we only need up to column 7 (index 6) for the analysis.

In [29]:
team_data_period_1 = NBA_Data.iloc[:152, :10]

Now the problem is that the data spans 8 years in the first bin. As such, teams are repeated. We don't want to have multiple points for the same team, so we need to find the Unique Team Names.

In order to do so, we will use the columnar "unique" function available for Pandas DataFrames.

In [31]:
teams_1 = team_data_period_1['Abbreviation'].unique()

Now we need to create a mini-array of the data we just extracted from the table. Let's use a loop over all the teams, adding the necessary info to a blank array.

The array we create here will come in handy later when we analyze the data and eventually plot it.

In [32]:
team_period_1 = []
for abbrev in teams_1:
    team_period_1.append(team_data_period_1[team_data_period_1.Abbreviation == abbrev])

Now that we have an array, we need to create a dataframe that we can use for plotting later.

In [33]:
team_data_1 = pd.concat(team_period_1)

Since there are roughly 8 years of data in each bin, we need to look at averages from the 8 year period. We will do this by calling the columnar "mean" function on the colums labeled Win % and Payroll.

In [34]:

Part 5: Analyzing on a level playing field¶

The American Currency is a volatile one, rising and falling year in and year out. In order to make our analysis more accurate and possibly provide a better recommendation, we need to standardize the payrolls so that the early years and later years are treated similarly.

Now that we have the teams and years that were present in the original dataset, we can now attempt to standardize the payroll column.

In [63]:
yearly_average_payroll = []
yearly_payroll_sd = []
annual_payroll_by_team = []
for year in NBA_Data['Season']:
    yearly_average_payroll.append(NBA_Data.loc[NBA_Data['Season'] == year, 'Payroll'].mean())
    yearly_payroll_sd.append(NBA_Data.loc[NBA_Data['Season'] == year, 'Payroll'].std())
    for abbrev in NBA_Data['Abbreviation']:
        annual_payroll_by_team.append(NBA_Data.loc[(NBA_Data['Season'] == year) & (NBA_Data['Abbreviation'] == abbrev), 'Payroll'])

The formula we will apply to standardize payroll is: $(payroll - payroll_j)/(sd_j)$ where $j$ represents the year

In [66]:
standardized_team_data['yearly_average'] = yearly_average_payroll
standardized_team_data['yearly_standard_deviation'] = yearly_payroll_sd
standardized_team_data['Standardized Payroll'] =  (standardized_team_data['Payroll'] - standardized_team_data['yearly_average'])/standardized_team_data['yearly_standard_deviation']

Part 6: Analyzing the data across time¶

Now that we have collected all the needed data and performed some cursory analysis and standardization, we need to be able to analyze our data through time. This will give us a better idea of how things have changed from 1985 to now.

In [77]:
standardized_team_data.plot(kind = 'scatter', x = 'Season', y = 'yearly_average')
Out[77]:
<Axes: xlabel='Season', ylabel='yearly_average'>

Just by looking at the plot, we can see that across the league, teams are paying more on average today than they were back in 1985. Also, we can see that averages appear to remain roughly constant over 5-year intervals, but jump sharply from one interval to the next.

However, we don't just want to look at the league as a whole. Let's split the league into east and west, analyzing how each conference spent over the 40 year study period.

To do this, we will make a plot known as a Violin Plot, which can be found in python's Seaborn Module.

In [78]:
import seaborn
In [79]:
seaborn.violinplot(x = standardized_team_data['Conf'], y = standardized_team_data['Payroll'])
Out[79]:
<Axes: xlabel='Conf', ylabel='Payroll'>

If we just plot by conference, it doesn't give us much information year-on-year, but we can see as a general trend that teams in the West tend to spend more money on average when compared to eastern conference teams, especially given the slightly higher median across the 40 year study.

Let's try to actually see how much more wins teams get by paying more. We will do this using the Statsmodels API.

Part 7: Gradient Descent¶

In this part, we will use an algorithm called Batch Gradient Descent in order to make the most accurate model for the period being studied. Furthermore, we will use the gradient descent model generated to make a final recommendation based on the assumption that we want to win a record number of games: $74/82$ or $90.24\%$

In [101]:
# Univariate 
X = 2*np.random.rand(100,1)
In [102]:
y = 49 + 1*X + np.random.randn(100,1)

The above two lines of code have just generated a placeholder model. This model is just a guess for what the actual model will be like.

In [103]:
plt.scatter(X,y)
Out[103]:
<matplotlib.collections.PathCollection at 0x7fdfe81a5810>

From the plot of the data, we can see that X and y share a positive correlation, and a strong one at that. This means that our initial guess is a good one and the actual model will be something similar.

In [104]:
#since there are 2 variables theta_0 and theta_1, we need two columns for the x-values
X_b = np.c_[np.ones((100,1)),X]
In [105]:
eta = 0.1
n_iterations = 1000
m = 100 #note, this is different from the 'm' representing the slope of the linear regression line
In [106]:
#As we are making random guesses for X and Y, so we must do the same for the Theta values
theta = np.random.randn(2,1)
In [107]:
for i in range(n_iterations):
    gradients = 2/m * X_b.T.dot(X_b.dot(theta)-y)
    theta = theta - eta*gradients
In [108]:
theta
Out[108]:
array([[48.76264002],
       [ 1.05357897]])
In [109]:
# Gradient Descent: We need to test theta values as we go, deciding whether we need to increase or decrease them to get the most optimal estimate
def grad_descent(X,y,T,alpha):
    m, n = X.shape
    theta = np.zeros(n)
    f = np.zeros(T)
    for i in range(T):
        f[i] = 0.5*np.linalg.norm(X.dot(theta)-y)**2
        g = np.transpose(X).dot(X.dot(theta)-y)
        theta = theta - alpha*g
    return(theta,f)
In [110]:
T = 500 #Number of timesteps (How many iterations?)
alpha = 0.0001 #the learning rate (How quickly does the model improve?)
theta,loss = grad_descent(X,y,T,alpha)
In [111]:
plt.plot(range(T),loss)
plt.ylabel("Loss")
plt.xlabel("Iterations")
plt.show()

As we can see from the loss curve, we can tell that our model got better as time went on. Now, with the Gradient Descent completed, it's time to make the final recommendation.

Our model is as follows: $Win Percentage = 48.76264002+1.05357897*Payroll$

Part 8: The final recommendation¶

You were hired by the team to let them know how much payroll they would need in order to win an NBA-record 74 games from the standard 82 game season. Calculation led to the determination that this win percentage would be approximately $90\%$.

Armed with your model, you plug in 90 for win percentage and attempt to solve.

What this yields is $ 90 = 48.76264002+1.05357897*Payroll$, which you solve, using basic Python.
